<section xml:id="sec-span" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Span</title>

 <p>
Recall from <xref ref="def-lincomb"/> that a vector <m>\vect{v} \in \R^n</m> is a 
linear combination of vectors <m>\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k \in \R^n</m> 
if
<me>
\vect{v} = c_1\vect{v}_1 + c_2\vect{v}_2 + \dots + c_k\vect{v}_k
</me>
for scalars <m>c_1, c_2, \dots, c_k \in \R</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="span">
<statement>
<p>Let <m>S = \{\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k\}</m> be a set of 
vectors in <m>\R^n</m>. The <term>span</term> of <m>S</m>, or the span of 
<m>\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k</m>, is the set of all linear 
combinations of <m>\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k</m>, and is 
denoted by <m>\lspan{(S)}</m> or 
<m>\lspan{(\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k)}</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
By definition,
<md>
<mrow>
\lspan{(S)} \amp  = \lspan{(\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k)}                                                                                             \\
\amp  = \{\vect{v} \in \R^n \; | \; \vect{v} = c_1\vect{v}_1 + c_2\vect{v}_2 + \dots + c_k\vect{v}_k \quad \text{for }\, c_1, c_2, \dots, c_k \in \R\}
</mrow>
</md>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-spans">
<statement>
<p>

  <ul>

  <li>
  <p> 
    Every span contains the zero vector since if 
<m>S = \{\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k\}</m> is any set of vectors 
in <m>\R^n</m>, we have 
<m>\vect{0} = 0\vect{v}_1 + 0\vect{v}_2 + \dots + 0\vect{v}_k</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    If <m>S = \{\vect{0}\}</m>, then
<md>
<mrow>
\lspan({\{\vect{0}\}}) \amp  = \{\vect{v} \in \R^n \;|\; \vect{v} = c\vect{0} \quad\text{for }\, c\in \R\} \\
\amp  = \{\vect{v} \in \R^n \;|\; \vect{v} = \vect{0}\}                             \\
\amp  = \{\vect{0}\}
</mrow>
</md>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    If <m>S = \{\vect{d}\}</m> for some <m>\vect{d}</m> in <m>\R^2</m> with 
<m>\vect{d} \ne \vect{0}</m>, then <m>\lspan{(S)}</m> is
<me>
\lspan({\vect{d}}) = \{\vect{x} \in \R^2 \;|\; \vect{x} = t\vect{d}\quad\text{for }\, t\in \R\}
</me>
which is the line through the origin with direction vector 
<m>\vect{d}</m>, as shown in <xref ref="fig-span-line"/>.


<figure xml:id="fig-span-line">
<caption>The span of <m>\vect{d}</m> is the dashed line through the origin</caption>
<image width="60%">
<latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}
    \draw [thick, -\gt] (-1.6, 0) -- (3, 0) node [right] {$x$};
    \draw [thick, -\gt] (0, -1.6) -- (0, 3) node [above] {$y$};
    \draw [very thick, -\gt] (0, 0) -- (1, 1) node [right] {$\vect{d}$};
    \draw [thick, dashed] (-1, -1) -- (2.5, 2.5);
\end{tikzpicture}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    If <m>S = \{\vect{d}, \vect{u}\}</m> for nonzero <m>\vect{d}, \vect{u}</m> 
in <m>\R^2</m> such that <m>\vect{d}</m> and <m>\vect{u}</m> are parallel, 
then <m>\lspan{(S)}</m> is still the line through the origin with direction 
vector <m>\vect{d}</m>. This is because since <m>\vect{d}</m> and <m>\vect{u}</m> 
parallel, we have <m>\vect{u} =c\vect{d}</m> for some <m>c\in \R</m>, so
<md>
<mrow>
\lspan{(\vect{d}, \vect{u})} \amp  = \{\vect{x} \in \R^2 \;|\; \vect{x} = t_1\vect{d} + t_2\vect{u} \quad\text{for }\, t_1, t_2\in \R\}   \\
\amp  = \{\vect{x} \in \R^2\;|\; \vect{x} = t_1\vect{d} + t_2(c\vect{d}) \quad\text{for }\, t_1, t_2\in \R\} \\
\amp  = \{\vect{x} \in \R^2 \;|\; \vect{x} = (t_1 + ct_2)\vect{d} \quad\text{for }\, t_1, t_2\in \R\}
</mrow>
</md>,
which is the line with vector form <m>\vect{x} = t\vect{d}</m>, for <m>t\in \R</m>.
  </p>
  </li>

  <li>
  <p> 
    If we take <m>\vect{d}</m> and <m>\vect{u}</m> in <m>\R^3</m> instead for the 
previous two examples, they still describe a line. On the other hand, if 
<m>S = \{\vect{u}, \vect{v}\}</m> for nonzero vectors <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v}</m> in 
<m>\R^3</m> which are not parallel, then
<me>
\lspan{(\vect{u}, \vect{v})} = \{\vect{x}\in \R^3 \;|\; \vect{x} = s\vect{u} + t\vect{v}, \quad \text{for }\,s, t \in \R\}
</me>
is the plane
<me>
\vect{x} = s\vect{u} + t\vect{v}, \qquad \text{for}\; s,t \in \R
</me>
through the origin in <m>\R^3</m> with direction vectors <m>\vect{u}</m> and 
<m>\vect{v}</m>, shown in <xref ref="fig-span-plane"/>.



<figure xml:id="fig-span-plane">
