  </p>
  </li>

</ul>

</p>
</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-checking-span">
<statement>
<p>
Is <m>[8, -5, -15] \in \lspan{([1, 2, 0], [-2, 3, 5]})</m>?
</p>

<p>
We need to look for <m>c_1, c_2 \in\R</m> such that
  <me>
  [8, -5, -15] = c_1[1, 2, 0] +c_2[-2, 3, 5]
</me>.
Comparing components gives the system of linear equations
<me>
\begin{cases}
  c_1 - 2c_2  \amp  = 8  \\
  2c_1 + 3c_2 \amp  = -5 \\
  5c_2        \amp  = -15
\end{cases}
</me>.
The third equation gives that <m>c_2 = -3</m>, and then the first equation gives 
that <me>
c_1 = 8+ 2c_2 = 8 + 2(-3) = 2
  </me>. 
These values also satisfy the second equation, since <m>2(2) + 3(-3) = -5</m>. So <m>[8, -5, -15] \in \lspan{([1, 2, 0], [-2, 3, 5]})</m>, with coefficients <m>c_1 = 2</m> and <m>c_2 = -3</m>.</p>
  </statement>
  </example>
  
<definition xml:id="def-spanning-set">
<statement>
  <p>Let <m>S = \{\vect{v}_1, \vect{v}_2, \dots, \vect{v}_k\}</m> be a set of 
  vectors in <m>\R^n</m>. If <m>\lspan{(S)} = \R^n</m>, we say that <m>S</m> 
  is a <term>spanning set</term> for <m>\R^n</m>.
  </p>
  </statement>
  </definition>

  <example xml:id="ex-stan-basis-spanning-set">
  <statement>
  <p>
  Recall the standard unit vectors <m>\vect{e}_1 = [1, 0]</m> and 
  <m>\vect{e}_2 = [0, 1]</m> in <m>\R^2</m>. The set <m>\{\vect{e}_1, \vect{e}_2\}</m> 
  is a spanning set for <m>\R^2</m>, since if <m>[x, y]</m> is an arbitrary vector 
  in <m>\R^2</m>, we have
  <me>
  [x, y] = x\vect{e}_1 + y\vect{e}_2 \in \lspan{(\vect{e}_1, \vect{e}_2)}.
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-is-spanning-set">
<statement>
<p>Determine whether <m>S = \{[1, 1], [-2, -2]\}</m> is a spanning set for 
<m>\R^2</m>.
</p>
<p>
We have that
<md>
<mrow>
\lspan{(S)} \amp  = \{\vect{x} \in \R^2 \;|\; \vect{x} = c_1[1, 1] + c_2[-2, -2], \quad\text{for }\, c_1, c_2 \in \R\} \\
\amp  = \{\vect{x} \in \R^2 \;|\; \vect{x} = (c_1-2c_2)[1, 1], \quad\text{for }\, c_1, c_2 \in \R\}        \\
\amp  = \lspan{([1, 1])}
</mrow>
</md>,
which is the line through the origin with equation <m>t[1, 1]</m>, 
for <m>t\in \R</m>. So any vector not on that line is not in <m>\lspan{(S)}</m>. 
We can check for example that <m>\vect{e}_1 \notin \lspan{(S)}</m>; if
<me>
\vect{e}_1 = c_1[1, 1] + c_2[-2, -2]
</me>
for <m>c_1, c_2 \in \R</m>, which simplifies to
  <me>
  [1, 0] = [c_1 - 2c_2, c_1 - 2c_2],
</me>
we can compare coefficients to get the system of linear equations
<me>
\begin{cases}
  1 \amp  = c_1 - 2c_2 \\
  0 \amp  = c_1 - 2c_2
\end{cases}
</me>.
This is inconsistent, so there are no solutions, so 
<m>\vect{e}_1 \notin \lspan{(S)}</m>. Hence <m>S</m> is not a spanning set 
for <m>\R^2</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
The issue is that <m>[-2, -2]</m> is parallel to <m>[1, 1]</m>, so it doesn't 
contribute anything extra to the span. In the language of the next section, we 
will say that <m>[1, 1]</m> and <m>[-2, -2]</m> are `linearly dependent'.
</p>

<p>
  We present the following two results without proof. It is a good exercise to at least think about why they are true.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-char-span">
<statement>
<p>
We have <m>\vect{b}\in\lspan(\vect{v}_1,\dots,\vect{v}_k)</m> if and only if the system with augmented matrix 
  <m>\begin{amatrix}{ccc} \vect{v}_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vect{v}_k \amp \vect{b}\end{amatrix}</m> is consistent.
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<theorem xml:id="thm-span-and-dimension">
<statement>
<p>
If <m>S</m> is a subset of <m>\R^n</m> and <m>\lspan(S)=\R^n</m>, then <m>S</m> has at least <m>n</m> elements.
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

</section>